					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>New Mexico Honors its Literature, PubWest Turns 30, Poet Insults Provo</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 11-14-07</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/thedeathatawahi_thumb.jpg" align="right" width="200" height="300" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p>The winners of the first annual <a target="_blank" href="http://nmbookaward.com/finalists.html" title="New Mexico Book Awards">New Mexico Book Awards</a> were announced recently in Albuquerque.&nbsp; Harold Burton Meyers&#8217; historical murder-mystery <a target="_blank" href="http://www.amazon.com/Death-Awahi-Harold-Burton-Meyers/dp/0896725995" title="The Death at Awahi ">The Death at Awahi </a>was named the best book of the year, and 1972&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bless_Me,_Ultima" title="Bless Me, Ultima">Bless Me, Ultima</a> by <a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudolfo_Anaya" title="Rudolfo Anaya">Rudolfo Anaya</a> won the People&#8217;s Choice Award.&nbsp; (Okay, that book has been on the shelves for over three decades, but this is the <I>first</I> annual NM Book Awards, so you can&#8217;t blame the People for choosing the beloved novel.)
</p>
<p>
Anaya and <a target="_blank" href="http://www.umsl.edu/~smueller/" title="Tony Hillerman">Tony Hillerman</a> were honored for their contributions to New Mexico literature, and awards were presented in a slew of other categories, including Best Arts Book, the title awarded to <a target="_blank" href="http://www.stephentrimble.net/" title="Stephen Trimble">Stephen Trimble</a>&#8216;s <I>Lasting Light: 125 Years of Grand Canyon Photography</I>, which was featured on <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_stephen_trimble/C78/L76/" title="NewWest.Net/Books earlier this year">NewWest.Net/Books earlier this year</a>.
</p>
<p>
<a target="_blank" href="http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6500402.html?nid=2286&amp;source=link&amp;rid=472909042&amp;" title="Publishers Weekly">Publishers Weekly</a> recently reported on the 30th Anniversary of the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.pubwest.org/" title="Publishers Association of the West">Publishers Association of the West</a>.&nbsp; The group celebrated its longevity in Park City, Utah last weekend.&nbsp;  According to PW, &#8220;Most of PubWest&#8217;s member publishers are niche and regional presses seeking to expand sales beyond the region and/or niche.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Just how Western is PubWest?&nbsp; According to <a target="_blank" href="http://www.pubwest.org/index.php?page_id=7" title="the organization's website">the organization&#8217;s website</a>, &#8220;West of the Mississippi, west of the Hudson, heck, west of the Atlantic! &#8216;West&#8217; is less about the geographical makeup of our publisher members than it is about the types of books we publish.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
<a target="_blank" href="http://www.gibbssmith.com/" title="Gibbs Smith">Gibbs Smith</a> was awarded the Jack D. Rittenhouse Award to honor his four-decade publishing career.&nbsp; According to PW, &#8220;Smith founded Gibbs Smith Publisher in 1969 and still runs the operation from a converted barn that originally housed livestock,&#8221; taking as his mission to &#8220;reverse the West being a colony in our own country.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Speaking of Utah, <a target="_blank" href="http://bookcriticscircle.blogspot.com/2007/11/straight-out-of-utah.html" title="Critical Mass">Critical Mass</a>, the blog of the National Books Critic Circle recently featured the poem &#8220;Provo&#8221; by NBCC Award-winner <a target="_blank" href="http://www.drunkenboat.com/db2/rudman/rudman.html" title="Mark Rudman">Mark Rudman</a>.&nbsp; It belongs to hallowed tradition of town insult poetry.&nbsp; Among the revelations in the poem: &#8220;It&#8217;s hard to get anywhere in Utah without going through Provo.&#8221;  The last stanza cuts the sharpest:
</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;O I guess it wasn&#8217;t that different from entering
<br />
A thousand other American towns, but this one
<br />
Made my flesh crawl. I wanted to howl.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>
Few in Provo will be surprised to learn that Rudman was <a target="_blank" href="http://www.drunkenboat.com/db2/rudman/rudman-about.html" title="born in New York City">born in New York City</a>.
</p>
<p>
Have some regional literary news or events to share?&nbsp; If so,  <script type="text/javascript">
